<br>
Depression is a serious medical condition that is biological in nature.<br>
There are many and varied triggers, however, one thing is certain, it IS a chemical imbalance in the brain, and that it is NOT something someone can just &quot;snap out of&quot;.<br>
NOR is it anything to be ashamed off.<br>
Depression is one of the top 5 diseases suffered in the world.<br>
<br>
Anti-depressants are not the &quot;be all and end all&quot;, obviously counselling and other &quot;non-pharmaceutical&quot; treatments should be used in conjunction with drug therapy.<br>
However, if a person is diagnosed with a clinical depression, I believe it is very important to start some form of antidepressant.<br>
The newer class of antidepressants, being those of the SSRI and SNRI groups are safer, cleaner, and have less side effects.<br>
Your Dr would of course choose the most appropriate for you.<br>
<br>
Anti depressants wont work overnight, nor will they &quot;change your life&quot;. What they do is get you back to a level where you are in control once more, and are more able to deal with the problems that may have contributed to the depression in the first place.<br>
